          <dm:component>Documentation</dm:component>
          <dm:product>SUSE Linux Enterprise High Availability &productnumber;</dm:product>
          <dm:assignee>tahlia.richardson@suse.com</dm:assignee>
       </dm:bugtracker>
        <dm:translation>yes</dm:translation>
      </dm:docmanager>
      <abstract>
      <variablelist>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>WHAT?</term>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              &ha; clusters require different preparation steps for different maintenance tasks.
              Use this workflow when making changes to the cluster nodes, such as hardware,
              software or firmware updates.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>WHY?</term>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              You must protect the cluster and its resources before performing maintenance tasks
              or you risk unwanted side effects such as resource failure, unsynchronized CIBs,
              or even data loss.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>EFFORT</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                Preparing a node for maintenance only takes a few minutes. In this scenario, most
                resources don't require downtime because the cluster moves them to other nodes, but
                some resources might stop if constraints prevent them from moving. The resources
                will still be highly available because only one node at a time is offline.
                <!-- Alternative: "If the cluster has three or more nodes, the resources will still
                 be highly available even while one of those nodes is offline." -->
              </para>
            </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>GOAL</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                Minimize risk and downtime while making changes to one or more cluster nodes.
                This workflow involves putting a node into standby mode and stopping the cluster
                services on just that node, then rebooting if required. Repeat these steps on one
                node at a time.
              </para>
            </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <!--varlistentry>
          <term>REQUIREMENTS</term>
            <listitem>
              <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    Can't think of any other than an existing &sleha; cluster, which is obvious
                  </para>
                </listitem>
              </itemizedlist>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry-->
        </variablelist>
        <important role="compact">
          <para>
            If this isn't the workflow you need, see <xref linkend="ha-maintenance-other-workflows"/>
            to choose the right one.
          </para>
        </important>
      </abstract>
